*BROKEN BUTTON/SCREEN RATIO PROBLEM SOLVED* Loved this game when I first got it. However, when installing on my S10+, none of the buttons work and the screen ratio was weird. For those with the same problem, go into: Settings >> Full Screen Apps >> Scroll down to Leo's Fortune >> Change Auto to Full Screen. After this, the buttons work much better and the screen ratio is almost perfect. Certainly much more playable/enjoyable. Hope this helps anyone else :)

to spend money! Thank You!

This game has the most gorgeous graphics from start to finish, the music 
and sound effects are also excellent. The game is a real joy to play, a 
little on the easy side if you want to rush through the twenty four levels 
taking advantage of the unlimited lives and restart points, which are never 
far from where you die, but to get all the stars and complete the game 
properly will take much longer than the couple of hours it takes to rush 
through. The game also has a really nice storyline which plays out between 
the levels, again with terrific graphics, which are in black and white. The 
puzzles are fairly easy, but still good fun to work out. All in all, a 
brilliant and clever platform game, and one of the best I have ever 
played... As a note to the developers of Leo's Fortune, I would suggest 
lives were not infinite, but limited at the start of each level with extra 
lives earned by collecting practically everything to be found in the level. 
The puzzles could be harder and more devious, requiring a bit more effort 
to work them out, and maybe a load of hidden extras requiring a lot more 
searching, like in the Donkey Kong games. One more thing, if you are not 
already doing so, PLEASE PLEASE PLEASE make either another Leo game, or 
something similar... 9.95 / 10

Great game. Worth the $5.  As everyone says the graphics are awesome. Really gorgeous looking levels and character model that show off the capability of mobile devices. When you can have a game look this good and still run @ close to 60 FPS, you have a good mobile game.   The soundtrack fits and adds depth. At no point have I felt annoyed by the soundtrack and muted the game so I could listen to my music while playing.    Gameplay is solid. At the games core Leo's Fortune is a physics based platformer with puzzles thrown in. Feels like Sonic the Hedgehog and World of Goo mixed together (in a good way). This is a game that could only exist as a mobile game and I like how the developers took advantage of this fact rather than trying to make the game something that would have been better if it was on PC.  Generous checkpoint system and faster paced gameplay are great for casual players. Global score (level time) and completion stars add replay value for purist and speed-runners.    Cons?  -24 levels @ 5 to 6 minutes each (1st playthrough) makes for a shorter game.  -Puzzles not hard enough? True. But this is a speed-running game. -Requires full attention and both hands

Like most "games" today, whoever programmed this thing does not know how to program in a "save game" routine.  So, you have to keep redoing the same, boring, stupid parts that are just exhausting.  Perhaps whoever coded this could consult with someone like the folks who wrote Skyrim so they can learn how to code save routines.  This game is nauseatingly repetitious at best.  It's perfect for people who aren't familiar with how really professionally coded games are written, but it doesn't fly with me.  I've long held that most game developers today have a secret disdain for their players and this game only fortifies that belief for me.  This game is a great example of how we in the U.S. have become accepting of slip shod quality and just don't care anymore.

1337 & Senri have created something special here. Leo's Fortune is a AAA platformer that feels like it was made for touch screen devices, and nothing was really sacrificed to accomplish this.  The story is told through Leo's mutterings to himself during gameplay and a few short cut scenes between the four sections of the game. The developers did a good job of crafting an immersive and intriguing story without it getting in the way of the gameplay too much. Something essential for mobile gaming.  The game is easy to pick up and play by anyone, and has no learning curves. I never felt frustrated by the controls, and the level design is smart and intuitive. You get the hang of gliding through the gorgeous environments fairly quickly.  I really can't say enough good things about this game. If you're looking for a fun, modern platformer for your phone and tablet, I can't recommend this highly enough.

Leo's Fortune is an excellent example of modern mobile gaming. At this price, it's never going to match console platformers for length, but what you do get is good value for money. As well as being well presented and quite funny, it also provides a decent challenge. And if you suck at platform games as much as I do, you'll be glad to know it's very forgiving when it comes to putting you back in the game when you die; you won't find yourself right at the start of the level or anything like that.   There are also no in-app purchases, so pay once and you get the whole game. No micro-transaction rip-offs here.   Oh, and it's compatible with the Moga Pro Power (in HID mode) and probably other controllers, so you don't have to rely on touch controls.
